commit.message:
feat: add btree scalar index (#1476)

This PR fleshes out the concept of a scalar index. It creates a
btree-inspired index as an initial example index. The index is modeled
very similarly to the vector index and will also closely resemble an IVF
index.

The index is broken into two parts, the lookup table / btree and the
data pages (leaf nodes). The lookup table is stored on disk as a lance
table with a single record batch containing the min/max/null
count/offset of each data page (the offset is currently superfluous and
I'll probably remove it as I clean this up). The data pages are stored
on disk as a lance table with one record batch per page. When we load
the lookup table into memory we convert it into a btree.

An index search first uses the btree to figure out which pages might
satisfy the query. We then load those pages into memory and search
through them with a flat scan. In the future we could investigate
storing leaf pages in some b-tree like structure but since they are
likely to be small enough to fit into a single IOPS I'm not sure there
would be much benefit.

To train, the btree index needs a stream of batches. These batches
should be rechunked into smallish chunks. Each batch should contain two
columns, the value and the row id. The batches should be sorted by the
value column. There is very little compute and the entire operation will
probably be I/O bound and fairly quick (however long it takes to sort
and scan the data) but memory intensive (no out-of-core sort yet).

The one parameter we have is the size of these data pages. For example,
we could decide each page is 4096 rows. This would mean, with 1Bi rows,
we would have 256Ki pages. Our lookup table should still be fairly small
(e.g. if the values are 4 byte integers then the lookup table will be
~3MiB.)

verification.payload:
tree 8e28090e79b386986028b497fc5347e2a9f6517b
parent 301c1dc8397dc2200c53bbddd7a853b0520237f6
author Weston Pace <weston.pace@gmail.com> 1698977881 -0700
committer GitHub <noreply@github.com> 1698977881 -0700

perf: dimension-based kernel for L2 and Cosine (#1503)

Provide faster routine for large PQ training, where each subvector only
has 8 floats.

L2:

```
L2(simd,f32x8)          time:   [1.9428 ms 1.9509 ms 1.9561 ms]
                        change: [-26.987% -25.863% -24.769%] (p = 0.00 < 0.10)
                        Performance has improved.
```

Cosine:

```
Cosine(simd,8-f32) rng seed
                        time:   [2.8588 ms 2.8693 ms 2.8960 ms]
                        change: [-62.852% -62.407% -61.952%] (p = 0.00 < 0.10)
                        Performance has improved.
```

commit.message:
fix: remove channel closed messages (#1502)

These messages are annoying, and all they are saying is the stream was
cancelled, which is generally intentional. We do take care to log error
messages that weren't able to be sent because of cancellation, to make
sure this doesn't mask any meaningful errors.

Fixes #1470

commit.message: ci: cancel in progress runs on new push (#1497) Adds concurrency config to cancel in progress actions when new commit pushed to PR or branch: https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#concurrency When we have a PR open, and we notice some CI job has failed, it's common to immediately push a new commit with the fix before all the jobs have finished. This will start a new batch of jobs for the PR, but the old ones will continue to run in the background and will possibly also fail. This leads to confusing behaviour where we'll later receive emails about failed jobs on a PR from old commits.

verification.payload: tree 0c03e6a130fc4a22bd912b84ef1a8fecb565ccd1 parent 4a742707075d4668bb4850166dc0957e3d8ba3d3 author Bert 1698851260 -0400 committer GitHub 1698851260 -0400 ci: cancel in progress runs on new push (#1497) Adds concurrency config to cancel in progress actions when new commit pushed to PR or branch: https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#concurrency When we have a PR open, and we notice some CI job has failed, it's common to immediately push a new commit with the fix before all the jobs have finished. This will start a new batch of jobs for the PR, but the old ones will continue to run in the background and will possibly also fail. commit.message: Bump version

feat: add parameter to split by file size (#1444)

It's possible to hit the max size for object-store (100GB). (This limit
is set by the multi-part upload implementation, not the underlying
stores themselves.)

To help users avoid this, we provide a new `max_bytes_per_file` settings
in `WriteParams`. This is checked as we flush each batch.

For users of the `Fragment.create()` API, we provide an alternative
called `write_fragments()` that can split into multiple fragments if
relevant limits are hit.

commit.message: Bump version

perf: use selection vector strategy to improve exact knn performance with deletions (#1418)

This PR repurposes the `_rowid` column's validity buffer as a selection
vector. By using a selection vector, we can defer the mem copies
involved with applying deletions to columnar data, which is a big
bottleneck in KNN queries with deletions.

For convenience, we make the `_distance` column nullable. The final
output will never be null, but we sometimes will have the intermediate
values be null.

Closes #1352

TODO: 
* [x] switch to using `_rowid` validity bitmap as selection vector.

commit.message:
test: fix flaky tests involving tokio::fs::File (#1430)

When a tokio::fs::File is dropped it does not wait for any ongoing
writes to finish (as this would be a synchronous blocking wait).
Instead, it is recommended that you call `shutdown` or `flush`. This was
causing some unit tests to fail intermittently because we were creating
a `File`, writing to it, then immediately reading from it. Sometimes
these reads would fail because the data had not actually been written
yet.

test: fix flaky tests involving tokio::fs::File (#1430)

When a tokio::fs::File is dropped it does not wait for any ongoing
writes to finish (as this would be a synchronous blocking wait).
Instead, it is recommended that you call `shutdown` or `flush`. This was

a `File`, writing to it, then immediately reading from it. Sometimes
these reads would fail because the data had not actually been written
yet.

commit.message:
perf: better parallelism in delete vector prefiltering (#1428)

The previous handling of delete files in an ANN search was sub optimal
in a few ways that are fixed by this PR:

* The synchronous portion of applying the prefilter was not run in
parallel across the different PQ pages. Now it is run in parallel as
part of the spawn_cpu critical section.
* The synchronous work of calculating the prefilter (converting from
delete file to, previously, a hashmap) was repeated for each PQ page.
Now we run this once, in parallel with the IVF centroid calculation and
any IVF/PQ page loading.
* The prefilter was using a computationally heavy HashSet. Now we use a
roaring treemap.

compacted fragments.

commit.message: Bump version

chore: cleanup tests to avoid errors when optional components are not present (#1374)

There are several mildly related changes here:

* I don't have torch installed in my environment and these supposedly
optional tests were failing. Even though the tests were checking for
this that check was not working correctly because `import torch` was
importing the `python/tests/torch` directory as a module. So I renamed
this to `torch_tests`.
* Marks allow you to make tests "opt out" but, for these optional
features (like integration tests) I think it's more intuitive to have
them be "opt in". I changed the way the integration test mark is
configured to allow for this.
* There was a cuda mark but I removed it in favor of checking if `torch`
is installed. Although, I don't think these things are exactly the same.
It's possible that a machine has torch but not cuda (because it has some
other GPU type). Ideally we would be able to detect if cuda is present
on the machine in some way and programmatically disable those tests (in
the `pytest_collection_modifyitems` method) similar to how the
integration mark is configured.

chore: cleanup tests to avoid errors when optional components are not present (#1374)

There are several mildly related changes here:

* I don't have torch installed in my environment and these supposedly
optional tests were failing. Even though the tests were checking for
this that check was not working correctly because `import torch` was
importing the `python/tests/torch` directory as a module. So I renamed
this to `torch_tests`.
* Marks allow you to make tests "opt out" but, for these optional
features (like integration tests) I think it's more intuitive to have
them be "opt in". I changed the way the integration test mark is
configured to allow for this.
* There was a cuda mark but I removed it in favor of checking if `torch`
is installed. Although, I don't think these things are exactly the same.
It's possible that a machine has torch but not cuda (because it has some
other GPU type). Ideally we would be able to detect if cuda is present
on the machine in some way and programmatically disable those tests (in
the `pytest_collection_modifyitems` method) similar to how the
integration mark is configured.
* I changed `make test` to now include `-W error::FutureWarning` so that
we can detect things like https://github.com/lancedb/lancedb/issues/548
more quickly

commit.message:
perf: improve KNN and ANN performance (#1367)

* Make sure we do `take_rows` with concurrency
* Use more optimized `concat` on FSL.
* Start opening fragments ahead of reading them
* Put IO tasks in `tokio::task::spawn()` so they can make progress
without the stream needing to be polled.

Closes #1360

commit.message: Bump version

fix: stop reading latest manifest (#1365)

As a quick fix to address safety/consistency issues, we will find the
latest manifest by scanning the `_versions` directory.

We continue to write the `_latest.manifest` file, so older readers are
still compatible.

Performance considerations: in object stores like S3, we can get 1,000
objects listed with 1 request. So right now this adds 1 IO for those
tables. Tables with more versions should probably have
`cleanup_old_versions` applied.

Fixes: #1356

We will optimize this in follow ups, as described in #1362
